Thank you for sharing how you've been building the dream team. And I would love to learn a little

00:07:12.079 --> 00:07:16.959
bit more while we're waiting for questions to come in about how you approach growing and

00:07:16.959 --> 00:07:27.600
developing your team. Yeah, absolutely. So I inherited some team members who were already

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:32.799
here. There were two when I came into the e-commerce analytics space, and then I grew

00:07:32.799 --> 00:07:38.959
people. I like a diversity in thought when I approach building an analytics team. So we took

00:07:38.959 --> 00:07:45.679
folks with direct domain experience and the member support agency who are interfacing with customers

00:07:45.679 --> 00:07:50.959
because I was trying to improve that e-commerce experience. We thought, well, let's get some folks

00:07:50.959 --> 00:07:55.279
that know it best. They've come from the front lines, but they also want to grow their career

00:07:55.279 --> 00:08:03.679
in data science. So I've grown people from that level, and then I also grow people who are kind of

00:08:03.679 --> 00:08:09.279
mid-level in their data analysis career and kind of get them to the next step. So how do you...

00:08:09.279 --> 00:08:15.359
And the most common pain point is like... And I got here in my career where it's like you spend

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:20.079
all this time building dashboards or building a presentation, and then you're like, okay, what next?

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:25.600
What are you going to do with that? And so I like to throw people over that loop and get them

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:30.000
thinking about how do I deliver insights? How do I deliver recommendations? Kind of like my favorite

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:37.200
part of it. But I start pretty nascent. At Peloton, we have in our central data science

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:44.239
team, we're kind of like a center of excellence model. And so we sit right alongside our data

00:08:44.239 --> 00:08:50.320
engineering team, and there's quite a bit of dev work that is expected from our data analysts all

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:55.760
the way up to our data engineers and data scientists that might not be expected on all

00:08:55.760 --> 00:09:01.840
the other teams that I'd work for. So I start real simple with folks. I pull up the terminal,

00:09:02.559 --> 00:09:07.679
and we start with Linux commands and things like that and build from there. And then we

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:13.760
start with Git. You've got to have some development skill on our team. And so

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:18.239
we practice what that means and kind of help them understand that I'm about to throw you

00:09:18.239 --> 00:09:22.479
for a loop here. We're about to do some things that are uncomfortable, but it's okay. You're

00:09:22.479 --> 00:09:30.640
supported, and you're going to be fine. And then beyond that, we start exposing our team

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:36.719
members to requests that come in that could be helpful to folks, like reporting. So there's

00:09:36.719 --> 00:09:42.080
always a need at Peloton to help people across the company understand what's going on,

00:09:42.799 --> 00:09:52.080
how many people are eligible for this promotion or this particular refund event because of where

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:56.719
they are in their post-sale process. So there's always opportunities like that where you can

00:09:56.719 --> 00:10:03.280
really get a team member's hands dirty early on, and they can understand the data warehouse, the

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:11.679
Mart, use BI tools. We use Looker and Tableau here at Peloton. So how can you create that report?

00:10:11.679 --> 00:10:20.479
And then after someone demonstrates their ability there, I start to put them in front of stakeholders

00:10:20.479 --> 00:10:29.599
more so and start to build that consult up. And the consult for me is really based in ensuring

00:10:29.599 --> 00:10:37.919
they can do design thinking and build empathy with that stakeholder and start to recommend,

00:10:37.919 --> 00:10:41.200
here's what you're asking me for, which typically stops at reporting, right?

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:50.320
But here's what I think you need to be asking me. Can you expand a bit on design thinking

00:10:50.320 --> 00:11:01.599
and what that means for your team? Yeah, so design thinking is an approach to really getting

00:11:01.599 --> 00:11:08.159
to know people and their pain points as you're trying to help them. So on my team, we have

00:11:09.679 --> 00:11:18.239
like four to five strong stakeholder groups where I have a, not a dotted line, but a real

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:24.239
strong relationship with a leader at Peloton. So let's say it's our extended warranty program.

00:11:25.119 --> 00:11:30.400
I get to know what's bothering that leader data-wise, like what is, what is, what are you on the

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:36.400
hook for? What are you struggling to measure? How much are you doing? How well are you doing it?

00:11:37.359 --> 00:11:49.359
What is your goal? And I try to help my team to build the same level of consult and empathy

00:11:49.359 --> 00:11:55.679
with their counterparts on that leader's team so that they can really provide helpful solutions

00:11:55.679 --> 00:12:03.840
with data. And that's been strong and it helps them think about

00:12:06.719 --> 00:12:12.000
how do they design their approach? Like what is this model that we're going to build really be

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.280
able to do? What are the actions that this person is struggling to do and how can I use data to help

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:23.919
with that? So it's really kind of like a brainstorming activity, but you're putting

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:27.840
yourself in the shoes of that stakeholder, getting to know them, figuring out how you

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:34.799
can be most helpful. I love that explanation. Thank you. That's so helpful. I see there's,

00:12:34.799 --> 00:12:39.840
there's a lot of questions starting to come in now. And one that came in on Slido was,

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:45.599
do you share any best practices or lessons learned from the e-commerce analytics team?

00:12:45.599 --> 00:12:56.559
Do you have a blog, for example? We do. We have a couple things that we do at Peloton that have

00:12:56.559 --> 00:13:02.479
really helped us to communicate about our successes. And we're going to be expanding

00:13:02.479 --> 00:13:09.760
upon these, but we have a newsletter that we work with our central project management team,

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:14.640
and we share our wins. We also share some things that we're struggling with that we call like

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:20.479
dirty laundry. It is just, you know, it's a startup, so nothing's perfect at Peloton.

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:26.479
But we share how we're working through some of those issues. And then my favorite thing that

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:32.880
we do is we have what we call a data town hall. And because we're that central analytics team,

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:39.280
sometimes it can be hard to have that sense of community with all the other analytics teams that

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:44.799
are at Peloton helping make decisions. So we set up this data town hall event, and we had

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:49.919
presenters from the e-commerce analytics space that talked about some of our most exciting models.

00:13:49.919 --> 00:13:54.960
Like Diana Morrell, who's on the call, spoke about her serial number of end stream model and

00:13:54.960 --> 00:14:01.919
all the use cases that have come from that, and kind of showcase this design thinking element

00:14:01.919 --> 00:14:07.359
and how she thinks like a data scientist. Those kinds of opportunities are really powerful.

00:14:08.239 --> 00:14:13.039
And in that same data town hall, we also talked about tech stack. We talked about

00:14:13.039 --> 00:14:19.599
programming approaches to ensure that our data models are well taken care of and documented for

00:14:19.599 --> 00:14:25.520
others, and made sure that people knew how our data engineering stack was evolving. So those are

00:14:26.080 --> 00:14:33.119
not only in the e-commerce analytics space, but a place where, yes, we share that.

00:14:33.119 --> 00:14:40.080
Now, if you're asking me externally if we post, we do not at this time, but I'm always encouraging

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:46.719
my team to blog and share their great work. That's awesome. I really like the idea of the

00:14:47.440 --> 00:14:50.880
data town hall event. How often does the team do those?

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:59.840
You know, it's a quarterly thing at this time. We're a distributed team, and resources are tight,

00:15:00.559 --> 00:15:05.760
especially right now with the state of the economy. But right now, we plan to do that quarterly.

00:15:06.719 --> 00:15:12.000
Cool. I see, Millie, you put a question into the chat just a little bit ago. Do you want to ask that

