live on the call? Sure. Yeah. Hey, Melissa.

00:15:17.679 --> 00:15:22.799
So I'm newer to the e-commerce space. I'm coming from higher education, and I'm now currently

00:15:22.799 --> 00:15:27.599
working as a senior data analyst at Thinks. And I was just wondering if you, since you also

00:15:27.599 --> 00:15:34.799
recently completed a degree, if you have any recommended e-commerce-specific resources or

00:15:34.799 --> 00:15:41.440
communities that you like to reach out to so I can, I guess, catch up on the metrics and lingo

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:49.760
and the analytics for e-commerce? Yeah, that's a really good question, Millie.

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:56.719
Hi. Welcome to the group. And congratulations to you on taking this step in your career and

00:15:56.719 --> 00:16:03.679
trying something new. That's just so admirable. And yeah, I'm familiar with Thinks as well.

00:16:03.679 --> 00:16:15.039
Very cool company. Yeah, you know, I am not, I think there's a few, there's a few particular

00:16:15.039 --> 00:16:22.640
areas where you might go out and find some critical KPIs for e-commerce.

00:16:23.359 --> 00:16:31.679
I would just research that like I would anything else, like Googling it. But what I

00:16:31.679 --> 00:16:39.599
can say is that, like, at Peloton, and in my team specifically, although my title is e-commerce

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:47.280
analytics, I don't, and my team never analyzed the kinds of metrics that you would think we would.

00:16:47.359 --> 00:16:52.080
So it's always been kind of this misnomer, like, for e-commerce analytics, Millie, one of the

00:16:53.599 --> 00:16:59.840
key metrics with this is really like for an engineering-based team. So it depends, like,

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:06.719
if your team is engineering-based and trying to constantly improve the engineering of your page,

00:17:07.280 --> 00:17:11.520
or if it's like more business-facing and you're just trying to do things like

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:17.280
report and help people understand the transactions, like the sales transactions.

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:21.920
So my team kind of played on that latter role where we're helping executives understand the

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:28.400
state of sales and post-sale activity for the members. But like conversion rate,

00:17:29.439 --> 00:17:34.880
that's one of the key metrics in e-commerce, like in the broader community. That's really

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:40.959
an engineering-facing metric at Peloton because all of the changes that those engineers make,

00:17:40.959 --> 00:17:46.000
they want to see, okay, am I driving conversion? Am I getting more sales through making this

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:51.599
particular change on the website? So that's one that I would definitely start to familiarize

00:17:51.599 --> 00:18:00.800
yourself with. And you may end up finding a community and sharing with me some of that

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:04.079
information, Millie. I wish I could be more helpful to you.

00:18:04.319 --> 00:18:05.599
All good. Thank you.

00:18:07.599 --> 00:18:11.599
I was just writing into the chat, too. I would love to try and gather some more

00:18:11.599 --> 00:18:18.719
retail examples that we've seen, too. And I'm thinking about the hangout a few weeks back with

00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:23.119
Jay from Harry Rosen, as well. That might be a helpful one to check out.

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:33.119
I see a few other Slido questions coming in, too. And one is, what are some of the

00:18:33.119 --> 00:18:36.719
biggest challenges of working with non-technical stakeholders?

00:18:36.719 --> 00:18:41.599
What are some of the biggest challenges of working with non-technical stakeholders?

00:18:45.599 --> 00:18:52.959
Yes. So one of the challenges first is communication.

00:18:55.040 --> 00:19:02.560
And figuring out how to resonate with a non-technical stakeholder when

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:07.680
your team and those that are working with you are primarily technical.

00:19:09.359 --> 00:19:15.599
You have that challenge of building trust. Trust is the first. That's the biggest thing.

00:19:15.599 --> 00:19:20.959
Right? They have to have an awareness and a belief that you're doing everything you can

00:19:20.959 --> 00:19:28.400
to provide that data product that's going to help them do better. And so I do think it does

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:34.719
go back to that design thinking, that empathy, and having enough humility to ask people,

00:19:35.599 --> 00:19:43.520
how can I really help you be better? And not having that belief as an analyst that you know

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:50.800
all the answers, because let me tell you, you do not. Numbers and data are only modeling what we

00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:57.599
have been modeled. They're a representation of the truth. But on the ground, operationally,

00:19:57.599 --> 00:20:04.959
there's always so much to learn. And you've got to really build those relationships with the folks

00:20:04.959 --> 00:20:12.959
that are on the ground that you're trying to help so they know you care. So they just know you care.

00:20:12.959 --> 00:20:18.079
And I think once you get over that hurdle and they know that you're trying to help them be

00:20:18.079 --> 00:20:25.040
a better version of themselves and do better at work, then you've got that inroads to start

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:30.400
passing them. Okay, here's this report that you were asking for. How can we make this better?

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:36.319
Or hey, I see you're really struggling with this. Did you know that this is the journey

00:20:36.319 --> 00:20:41.839
that you're on and you've made this much improvement? Or you know what, it looks like

00:20:41.839 --> 00:20:49.520
we're getting worse in this area. I'm seeing a negative trend here. So it's really trust first,

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:55.520
then communication and figuring out to what extent do you need to read into that

00:20:55.520 --> 00:21:01.280
person's technical capability and dial back all the things that you know. And this is

00:21:01.280 --> 00:21:07.599
the hardest thing for me to tell my people. It's like, I care about your technical know-how and

00:21:07.599 --> 00:21:13.920
your technical progression, but your stakeholder oftentimes does not, especially if they are

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:19.040
a non-technical person. It just overwhelms them. And if you're talking about

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:25.520
programs that you're using or the statistical elements and you're not being careful about how

00:21:25.520 --> 00:21:34.560
you're positioning that, it can become very unapproachable very quickly. So it's definitely

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:43.839
a soft skill in an area that must be developed in order to truly get use cases into production.

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:55.119
Thank you. I see that Thamalu, apologies if I'm pronouncing your name incorrectly,

00:21:55.119 --> 00:22:00.800
asked a question into the chat. And I'm not sure if you're still on, so I'm going to ask it live,

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:06.880
but feel free to jump in and add context too. But the question was, how do you identify data

00:22:06.880 --> 00:22:15.520
loss due to system issues? They said that's part of my job I find very stressful. Okay.

00:22:18.239 --> 00:22:24.239
So data loss due to systems issues. It's so funny because we had a situation like this come up

00:22:24.239 --> 00:22:34.400
yesterday. So I think with that now, I will say this is not what I do in my everyday today role,

00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:43.280
but I've done this role before earlier on. And I think it's a matter of laying out and understanding

00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:49.040
the architecture first of the systems that are supposed to talk to one another. So when you

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:54.800
understand the process flow and the lineage of the data as it moves through, let's say from your

00:22:54.800 --> 00:23:03.920
customer. So let's say your customer enters in their name on your website. And then you go and

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:12.160
